          <text>
            The mushroom paste sits heavy in my stomach — not unpleasant, just _present_. Real food — actual nutrition.

            One more survival basic checked off.

            I sit in my quarters, Scout settled nearby, and let myself think beyond the next crisis for the first time since the crash.

            Wound — healing. Food — established. Shelter — functional. Water — available.

            I'm alive — surviving and adapting to bureaucratic plant life through sheer stubborn determination and strategic phrasing.

            But I'm also still stranded on an alien planet with no ship, no crew, no way home.

            Rescue seems… unlikely.

            The _Meridian_ went down somewhere we weren't supposed to be — FTL malfunction, maybe, or something worse — far from trade routes. Even if someone noticed we were missing — finding me here, on an uncharted planet in the Outer Reaches?

            The math isn't good.

            I say (quietly), "Buddy — what's our realistic timeline for rescue?"
            —
            Holloway replies, in a warm, fluting voice, "Based on last known position and standard search protocols — if rescue operations were initiated immediately upon our disappearance, search radius would take approximately six to eight months to reach this system. Accounting for detection difficulties of uncharted planets, potential delays, and probability factors…"

            I say, "Just tell me."

            Holloway replies, "*Twelve to eighteen months.* Minimum. If they search at all."
            ¶
            There it is — a year, maybe more, maybe never — living on mushroom paste and bureaucratic forms.

            Scout rolls closer, pressing against my leg. Comfort or commiseration — both, probably.

            I ask, "Is there anyone here who could help — with unusual situations? Someone with more… authority?"

            Holloway responds — a fruiting body sprouts near the entrance.

            Holloway says, in that same warm fluting voice, "Authority for unusual situations? Most coordination happens through collective consensus. But for truly exceptional cases, we have Elder Heartwood."

            I sit up straighter. I say, "Elder Heartwood?"

            Holloway rustles — uncertainty. "Elder Heartwood is… distant, geographically and temporally. They exist in slow time — growth cycles measured in seasons, thought processes taking days or weeks. Communication is challenging."

            I swallow the dull hope. I ask, "But possible?"

            Holloway replies, "Yes! We can file a formal query through established channels. Elder Heartwood does respond to requests for guidance — eventually."

            I say, "How eventually?"

            Holloway replies, "Typical response time for standard queries — four to six weeks. For complex exceptional cases like yours — perhaps two to three _months_."

            «Months».

            Of course. Nothing here happens quickly.
          </text>
