          <text>
            But still — an actual authority. Someone who handles exceptions. Someone who might understand "help this human get home" as a valid request beyond standard protocols.

            I say — "I want to file that query. Whatever the formal process is."

            Holloway says — "Wonderful! This is very appropriate use of exception-handling channels. I'll prepare the documentation immediately!"

            Forms — obviously there will be forms. But I'm learning to work within this system — I can do forms, and I can wait months if it means a chance.

            Over the next hour, Holloway guides me through the formal query process.

            Petitioner Information: Full name, arrival circumstances, current status.
            Nature of Exception: Stranded non-plant lifeform requiring assistance beyond standard protocols.
            Requested Guidance: Recommendations for long-term survival, potential contact with human civilization, any available transportation or communication resources.
            Supporting Documentation: Medical records, crash site location, resource requirements, adaptation challenges.

            Buddy provides data — I provide context — Holloway documents everything with meticulous care. Scout watches the whole process, occasionally bouncing encouragingly.

            Holloway announces — "Query complete! I'll transmit this through the network to Elder Heartwood's grove. Response timeline — estimated eight to twelve weeks, accounting for processing time and Elder Heartwood's deliberation pace."

            Eight to twelve weeks.

            ¶

            Two to three months of bureaucratic plant life — of morning wellness checks and dietary assessments, of mushroom paste meals and wound care documentation. Two to three months of waiting.

            But also — hope. Actual hope.

            I say — "Thank you. Seriously — for filing this, for helping."

            Holloway says — "Of course! This is exactly the kind of exceptional situation Elder Heartwood exists to address. You should receive guidance eventually."

            «Eventually»

            The word hangs there — simultaneously reassuring and exhausting.

            Holloway continues warmly — "In the meantime, you're adapting remarkably well! Your progress with protocols has been excellent. We're very pleased with your integration."

            Integration — like I'm joining their community instead of being stranded with no other options. But aren't I, though? I'm learning their language, working within their systems, building routines — adapting.

            I say — "I'm trying."

            Holloway asks — "It shows! Now, shall we schedule your next wellness check for tomorrow morning?"

            Daily wellness checks — for months, maybe years. This is my life now.

            But also — I've filed the query, started the process, reached for the one authority who might actually help beyond forms and protocols. It isn't giving up — it's strategic patience.

            I say — "Yes. Schedule the wellness check."

            Scout bounces approvingly.

            Later, lying on the soft moss and woven plant fibers that serve as bed, I stare at the bioluminescent ceiling and take stock.
          </text>
