          <text>
            Three days since the crash — three days since my entire world exploded.

            I've survived impact, treated severe injury, met alien sentient plants who learned human language from HR manuals, navigated bureaucratic onboarding, established food sources through fungal chemistry, and filed formal exception queries with ancient tree authorities.

            My life has become surreal, absurdist science fiction — and somehow I'm managing it.

            Scout settles near the entrance — a constant guardian, non-verbal companion, there for everything: every crisis, every form, every exhausted moment.

            I say softly into the dim light —
            "Thanks. For sticking with me."

            Scout bounces once — gentle, understanding.

            I tell the ceiling —
            "Two to three months."

            I tell myself —
            "I can do two to three months. I've done three days. I can do more."

            Because what choice do I have? But also — because I can: I'm learning this system, getting better at it, phrasing requests strategically, working with each plant's strengths, finding humor in the absurdity.

            Adapting, surviving, and now — _maybe_ — finding a way out.

            Elder Heartwood — whoever they are, whatever wisdom they hold.

            The query is filed — the wait has begun.

            I close my eyes.

            ¶

            Tomorrow there will be more forms, more wellness checks, more mushroom-paste meals — but also: another day survived, another day closer to answers, another day of strange, absurd, bureaucratic life on an alien planet.

            I can do this — have to do this — am doing this — one impossible adaptation at a time.
          </text>
